<p><em>Cabaret Voltaire</em>: â€œIn June 1977, all three members of Cabaret Voltaire joined Marsh, Adi Newton, Glenn Gregory, Martyn Ware and 2.3â€™s drummer Hayden Boyes-Weston for one gig only as the punk-spoof supergroup The Studs. â€˜It was an anarchic raw event,â€™ recalls Newton. â€˜One of our helpers had a bag of pigsâ€™ ears which were liberally thrown at the audience.â€™ After chaotic improvised versions of The Kingsmenâ€™s â€˜Louie Louieâ€™, Lou Reedâ€™s â€˜Viciousâ€™ and Iggy Popâ€™s â€˜Cock in my Pocketâ€™, plus a bizarre version of theÂ <em>Dr Who</em>Â theme, the band left the stage to howls of abuse.â€ (p.158)</p>

<p><em>Throbbing Gristle</em>: Genesis P-Orridge, founder of TG, frequently underlined that the band wereÂ <em>anti-music</em>:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>P-Orridge and crew were sceptical about punkâ€™s credentials as radical music â€“ it was too rock, tooÂ <em>musical.</em>Â Speaking in the famous â€˜New Musickâ€™ November 1977 issue ofÂ <em>Sounds</em>, P-Orridge declared thatÂ <em>Sniffinâ€™ Glue</em>â€™s exhortation â€˜Hereâ€™s three chords, now start a bandâ€™ conceded far too much to traditional musicality. â€˜It starts with chords. Theyâ€™re saying â€œBe like everyone else, you gotta learn to playâ€. You can start withÂ <em>no chords</em>. Why not just say, â€œForm a band and it doesnâ€™t matter what it sounds like or whether you even make a noise, if you just stand there silent for an hour, just do what you want.â€â€™ [â€¦] At one early gig â€“ the Nagâ€™s Head, High Wycombe, February 1977 â€“ P-Orridge poured scorn on the jeering punks in the audience: â€˜You canâ€™t have anarchy and haveÂ <em>music</em>.â€™ During the cacophonous performance, Cosey bared her tits and P-Orridge poured fake blood over his head. Then he invited half a dozen kids from the audience onstage and handed them instruments. (p.230)</p>
